	   <tr><td colspan=2>Argfeld while your argument there is indeed well spoken I disagree whole heartedly with your opinions about loot distribution, and point systems.<br><br>I used to be in a DKP-oriented &quot;capable&quot; guild, and lived through the very painful demise of that guild. Sure it's still around, in name, but there's perhaps 5 people left in that guild who just won't let go... (hard to do when someone has given you leadership to what once was a great thing). After DKP that guild became littered with greed. Raid times where scheduled within a 3 hour window to benefit leadership only, who being in Japan or the Pacific region of the world, meant for the majority of the Eastern North Americas and Europe... was while we were asleep. Members living in these areas lost sleep just to &quot;get points&quot;... something that lost it's appeal pretty quickly. Members who could raid regularly during these times raked in far more points than those who did not, and as a result whenever an item like this dropped... it was very likely that a Ranger or even a Cleric was in a position to outbid the Monk, even if it wasn't much of an upgrade or possibly just a part-time fashion trophy... and most times this is EXACTLY what happened, all the time.<br><br>I've since joined some old friends in a guild just as if not more capable that that one... and although suggestions to go Point System Oriented comes up... the majority know of it's folley and we're dead set against it. It will just never happen... period. Does this fact make us a weaker guild... because we're not DKP? Hell no... in fact 120 members and growing strong with almost zero membership turnover... one of the oldest guilds on Xegony is proud to still be DKP free and raiding some of the higher tier areas of the game.<br><br>People are going to argue about loot... DKP or not. It's just something that happens in this game, and no system is going to control the fact that some things are just too damned rare (rare drops off rare spawns with rare availabilty). There's some sort of bizarre &quot;panic mode&quot; that players will go into when something like these legs drop... everyone who can use them, wants them for whatever reason, and gets paniced thinking they are the only ones that will ever drop in their game career. This of course is untrue.<br><br>While indeed the weight and stats appear to obviously benefit a Monk very well, it can be argued as well that the AC and 50 HPs gained from this item would benefit any class listed as eligible for them, and for Plate wearing classes, the zero weight factor makes up for the multitude of 15-25 weight items designated for these classes that Everquest is littered with.<br><br>I myself play a Cleric, and while my class is listed I wouldn't roll on them... no mana, no wisdom, nothing that helps my manapool and heck even Thurg legs help me more in that area. But with AC caps increased and mobs hitting melees for insane amounts of damage, I'd say this would benefit a Warrior (specifically an MT) who hasn't reached his extended AC cap or would like to free another AC slot for another item benefitting other stats extremely well.<br><br>In a nutshell I too am of the opinion that if an item lists certain class types, then it's &quot;intended&quot; for those classes to use should they desire. Unless it says &quot;monk only&quot;... who gave anyone the right to determine who is allowed to have it?<br><br>Just my 2 coppers <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
